File Inspect

%sh

# list the first two files in the directory, make sure the header file exists
# note - A little trick I use is to write just the headers to a delimited file, that sorts to the top of your file glob. 
#        When reading a glob of unheadered files, spark looks for the first row (the first file) and can find the hearders and use them. 

hdfs dfs -ls "/user/feeds/gdelt/events/*.export.CSV" | head -2
echo ">"
echo ">"

# this is a quick inspection check for headers, and delims
hdfs dfs -cat "/user/feeds/gdelt/events/*.export.CSV" | head -4 | column -t -s $'\t' | colrm 68

val InputFilePath = YourFilePath

val RawData = sqlContext.read
                           .format("com.databricks.spark.csv" )                 // set the csv library to use
                           .option("header"   , YourHeader    )                 // configurable headers
                           .option("delimiter", YourDelimeter )                 // configurable delimeters
                           .option("treatEmptyValuesAsNulls", "true")           // can be handy if you need to handle empty values
                           .option("nullValue", "NULL"        )                 // set a default char if nulls seen
                           .option("inferschema", "false"     )
                           .option("mode", "dropMalformed"  )                   // ignore malformed input records, vs default "permissive" mode // you may need this one day.
                           .load(InputFilePath)                                 // configurable file path. You can use wildcards.

// this file reader accessed the data via the schema
RawData.registerTempTable("RawData")                                            // register the data as a temp table, so SQL can access it
RawData.cache()                                                                 // cache the data into ram

val RawLines = sc.textFile(InputFilePath)                                       // this is a second file reader, but of unstructured raw lines.
RawLines.toDF.registerTempTable("RawLines")                                     // register this alternative method of access to the data

// as a double check, print out the schema we found:
RawData.printSchema()

paragraphs.title: Generate UTF Hex Metrics
paragraphs.text:
// load the UTF lookup tables

val codePointsSchema = StructType(Array(
    StructField("CodePoint"                 , StringType, true), //$1       
    StructField("Category"                  , StringType, true), //$2     
    StructField("CodeDesc"                      , StringType, true) //$2
    ))

val UnicodeCatSchema = StructType(Array(
    StructField("Category"                  , StringType, true), //$1       
    StructField("Description"               , StringType, true)  //$2     
    ))

val codePoints = sqlContext.read
                           .format("com.databricks.spark.csv")              // set the csv library to use
                           .option("header", "false")                       // configurable headers
                           .schema(codePointsSchema)
                           .option("delimiter", "\t" )                      // configurable delimeters
                           .load("/user/feeds/ref/codepoints2.txt")         // configurable file path. You can use wildcards.

codePoints.registerTempTable("codepoints")
codePoints.cache()
val utfcats = sqlContext.read
                           .format("com.databricks.spark.csv")              // set the csv library to use
                           .option("header", "false")                       // configurable headers
                           .schema(UnicodeCatSchema)
                           .option("delimiter", "\t" )                      // configurable delimeters
                           .load("/user/feeds/ref/UnicodeCategory.txt")     // configurable file path. You can use wildcards.

utfcats.registerTempTable("utfcats")
utfcats.cache()

// Next we build the different presentation layer views for each mask
val hexReport = sqlContext.sql("""
select
r.Category
, r.CodeDesc
, sum(maskCount) as maskCount
from
    ( select
            h.*
            ,c.*
        from Metrics_HEX h
        left outer join codepoints c
            on ( upper(h.MaskType) = c.CodePoint)
    ) r 
group by r.Category, r.CodeDesc
order by r.Category, r.CodeDesc, 2 DESC
""")
hexReport.registerTempTable("hexReport")
hexReport.cache()

hexReport.show(1000)

paragraphs.title: Column Population Checks
paragraphs.text:
val pop_qry = sqlContext.sql("""
select * from (
    select
    fieldName as rawFieldName
    ,   coalesce( cast(
                regexp_replace(fieldName, "C", "") as INT), fieldName) as fieldName
    ,   case when maskType = 0 then "Populated"
             when maskType = 1 then "Missing"
        end as PopulationCheck
    , coalesce(maskCount, 0) as maskCount
    ,    metricDescriptor as fileName
    from Metrics_POPCHECKS
) x 
order by fieldName
""")

val pivot_popquery = pop_qry.groupBy("fileName","fieldName").pivot("PopulationCheck").sum("maskCount")
pivot_popquery.registerTempTable("pivot_popquery")
val per_pivot_popquery = sqlContext.sql("""
Select 
x.* 
, round(Missing/(Missing + Populated)*100,2) as PercentMissing
from
    (select 
        fieldname
        , coalesce(Missing, 0) as Missing
        , coalesce(Populated,0) as Populated
        , fileName
    from pivot_popquery) x
order by x.fieldname ASC
""")
per_pivot_popquery.registerTempTable("per_pivot_popquery")
per_pivot_popquery.select("fieldname","Missing","Populated","PercentMissing","fileName").show(1000,false)
